frameDefinitions: In this frame, an Authority allows a Protagonist to know (in some way) that they may or may not engage in an Action.
The words in this frame describe an Experiencer's feelings of tolerating with respect to some Content.

In this frame a Hindrance makes it more difficult for a Protagonist to complete their intended Action or a Hindrance directly affects an Action where the Action can be a natural act or the actions of many individuals in a collective endeavor.

This frame concerns an Addict's physiological or psychological compulsive dependence on an Addictant, the substance or behavior to which the Addict is addicted. '' 'Although she was never a big fan of drugs, she became hooked on that designer drug instantly.'
A Topical_entity has properties which are affected by the existence and association of an Entity.
This frame contains  words for individuals, i.e. humans, with respect to their  proximity of residence.
frameExamples: The police officer <t>forbid</t> me from turning around .
He could not <t>tolerate</t> the smell of coconut .
Malcolm was <t>hindered</t> by his drinking problem .
Although she was never a big fan of drugs, she became <t>hooked</t> on that designer drug instantly.
By the 1920s a characteristic book <t>had</t> black and white photographic illustrations only .
The dead included homeowner Todd Underfoot, 33, his wife Spring Back Underfoot, 32, their <t>housemate</t>, Luisa Life, 46, and two of the Underfoot's three children.
listRoleDefinitions: The <fen>Authority</fen> orders the <fen>Protagonist</fen> to not engage in a particular <fen>Action</fen>.
The <fen>Protagonist</fen> wants to engage in an <fen>Action</fen>, but is ordered not to by the <fen>Authority</fen>.
The <fen>Action</fen> is what the <fen>Protagonist</fen> seeks to do, but is ordered not to.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the denying of permission occurs.
The <fen>Place</fen> is where the denial of permission occurs.
The <fen>Experiencer</fen> experiences tolerance with respect to the <fen>Content</fen>.

<fen>Content</fen> is what the <fen>Experiencer</fen>'s feeling of tolerance is directed towards..  The <fen>Content</fen> differs from a stimulus because the <fen>Content</fen> is not construed as being direcly responsible for causing the emotion.
The <fen>Topic</fen> is the area about which the <fen>Experiencer</fen> has the  tolerated experience(s).
The <fen>State</fen> is the abstract noun that describes a more lasting experience by the <fen>Experiencer</fen>.
The <fen>Event</fen> is the occasion or happening that <fen>Experiencer</fen>s in a certain emotional state participate in.
The time at which the <fen>Experiencer</fen> is in the state of toleration.
The <fen>Protagonist</fen> is the entity that tends towards or plans some <fen>Action</fen> which the <fen>Hindrance</fen> causes to be more difficult.
The <fen>Hindrance</fen> is the force which makes the <fen>Action</fen> more difficult or less likely to be successfully completed. The <fen>Hindrance</fen> may be a lack of enabling force:

The <fen>Action</fen> is what the <fen>Protagonist</fen> desires to do, which is made more difficult by the <fen>Hindrance</fen>. It can also be a natural act or collective endeavor, not linked to an overt <fen>Protagonist</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> is when the <fen>Hindrance</fen> affects the <fen>Protagonist</fen> or <fen>Action</fen>.
The <fen>Place</fen> is the location where  he <fen>Hindrance</fen> affects the <fen>Protagonist</fen> or <fen>Action</fen>.
The <fen>Addict</fen> is physiologically or psychologically dependent on a substance or a behavior.
<fen>Addictant</fen> is the substance or behavior to which the <fen>Addict</fen> is dependent.
Some entity, abstract or concrete, which is stated to exist and be associated with the <fen>Topical_entity</fen>.
The entity under discussion, whose states and properties are impacted by its association with the <fen>Entity</fen>.
The time at which the <fen>Entity</fen> exists and is associated with the <fen>Topical_entity</fen>
The place where the <fen>Entity</fen> is associated with the <fen>Topical_entity</fen>.
The individual(s) that serve(s) as a reference point for the definition of the <fen>Indicated_resident</fen> due to the proximity of residences.
A person or group of people defined in terms of the fact that they reside in the proximity of the <fen>Known_resident</fen>.
The individuals who reside in proximity to each other.
listRoleExamples: Everyone must endure <fex>some disappointments in life</fex>.
They 're very tolerant <fex>about boys' mess in the home and untidiness generally</fex>.
Tracy was in a surprisngly tolerant <fex>mood</fex> today.
<fex>When they are young,</fex>, they  cannot stand extremes of temperature.
The project was hampered <fex>by a lack of funds</fex>.
I have no problem with him becoming <fex>Madonna's</fex> neighbour at all!
